Results of Pilot coding exercise: 5 LIDD coders

Overview

This report presents the results of the LIDD pilot coding exercise for Switzerland based on the Silagadze & Gherghina (hereafter SG) policy typology.

The following bullet points include some of the main parameters of the coding analysis as presented below.

  • 30 referendum events were randomly selected)

  • 5 LIDD coders submitted their pilot coding (the coders are referred to as coders, 1 to 5)

  • Two measures of reliability are used. An (i) agreement measure and an (ii) intercoder reliability measure.

  • The agreement measure. Agreement between a pair of coders is quite easy to understand. If coders 1 and 2 coded 100 referendums and agreed (assigned the same codes) to 60 referendums, then the level of agreement would be 60% (disagreement would be 40%).

  • The intercoder reliability measure. The methodological literature uses a metric called intercoder reliability to measure the degree of agreement between coders rating items (referendum topics in our case). This measure is a bit more sophisticated and takes into account things like the level of agreement that could be achieved by chance (random answering). Its called the Kappa intercoder reliability measure.

  • The Kappa score can vary from -1 to 1. It was suggested by the author of the Kappa measure that the score could be interpreted as follows: values less than 0 indicate no agreement; and 0.010.20 as none to slight; 0.210.40 as fair; 0.410.60 as moderate; 0.610.80 as substantial; and 0.811.00 as almost perfect agreement.

Agreement among LIDD coders

The table below presents the two measures across the pairs of LIDD coders. With five LIDD coders, we have 10 possible pairwise comparisons. The Kappa value in the last row is the measure of intercoder reliability among the 5 LIDD coders, which at .29 is rather poor.

LIDD coder pair Agreement % Kappa (intercoder reliability)
c2 vs c4 93.3 0.90
c1 vs c2 80.0 0.72
c1 vs c4 80.0 0.72
c4 vs c5 80.0 0.71
c1 vs c5 76.7 0.68
c2 vs c5 73.3 0.62
c1 vs c3 66.7 0.58
c3 vs c5 60.0 0.49
c3 vs c4 56.7 0.44
c2 vs c3 56.7 0.43
All 50.0 0.29

Below we check reliability by removing one coder at each iteration. Instead of five coders there are now four coders. Removing any coder is likely to boost Reliability. Below we can see the combination (in the first row) that yields the highest reliability, coders 1,2,4,5.

Preliminary note on the definitions

These are comments on the definitions for further discussion.
ID Category Definition Issues
1 Constitution All referendums on adoption of a new constitution or on approval of constitutional reform regarding major changes. We cluster all other cases where certain constitutional issues were put on ballot according to the field of policy. We look in detail at what the amendment was about and categorize it according to the topic. Note the last sentence, about looking in detail at each amendment.
2 State Formation State formation includes all referendums on independence; referendums on whether an entity should remain part of a state or become part of another state; referendums on a new territorial composition of a state or on the continued existence within the same territory. Not great, but passable.
3 Political/Electoral System The referendums on the political system refer to popular votes about the form of government; distribution of power; the introduction or abolishment of new political institutions, and electoral system issues. OK
4 Interior Policies The interior policy referendums include popular votes on basic rights; laws on citizenship; particular regulations; legal framework (e.g.land law reform); or administrative reorganization. Very bad definition; Needs definition of what it includes since it is an SG concept but it can be interpreted in different ways.
5 Foreign Affairs The foreign affairs category includes all topics of interstate relations, such as: border/territory issues; international arrangements; international/supranational collaboration (e.g.European integration). OK, largely because we have a good idea of what is a foreign policy issue rather than the precision of the definition.
6 Economy Among the problems with this definition is that it also includes ownership issues, which are also mentioned in interior policy Among the problems with this definition is that it also includes ownership issues
7 Environment The environment category includes referendums on nuclear plants, general policies concerning the environment. OK, because we already have a notion of what it means
8 Health Health policies refer to specific issues or to general issues about the healthcare system. OK, because we already have a notion of what it means
9 Education The education policies refer to both higher education and school policies. OK, because we already have a notion of what it means
10 Moral & Ethics The relatively broad category of family, ethics and moral issues includes referendums on same-sex marriage, divorce, abortion, the death penalty and other moral issues. There is no definition here.
11 Labour & Social The labour and social issues include referendums on labour regulations, pensions, trade unions, social policies. OK, because we already have a notion of what it means
12 Media The media category includes all referendums on broadcasting rights and further regulations related to media landscape. OK, because we already have a notion of what it means
